---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import ConceptPageHero from '../../components/concepts/ConceptPageHero.astro';
import ConceptPager from '../../components/concepts/ConceptPager.astro';
import { getConcept } from '../../lib/concepts';

const c = getConcept('gravitation');
---

<Layout title={`${c.title} | Identity Engineering`}>
	<main class="min-h-screen">
		<ConceptPageHero
			scene={c.scene}
			tag={`${c.tag} · ${c.layerLabel}`}
			title={c.title}
			lede={c.blurb}
			scrollHint={c.scrollHint}
		/>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 px-6 py-24">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-8 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Interactive layer</div>
				<h2 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-white md:text-4xl">
					The first force between identities — and the tension it creates.
				</h2>
				<p>
					<strong class="text-white/80">Gravitation</strong> is the attractive force that results from the curvature of a high-mass vision. Where Curvature shapes possibility for one identity, Gravitation is what that shape does to other identities: pull, orbit, alignment, resistance — and the interactive tension this relationship produces.
				</p>
				<p>
					In the framework this opens the <strong class="text-white/80">Interactive Identity</strong> layer. A single geometry can be complete in itself. Once it is strong enough, forces appear between stems — and with them, new layers of tension.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 bg-white/[0.02] px-6 py-24">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
				<div class="mb-6 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Gravitation and Interactive Tension</div>
				<p class="text-lg text-white/55 mb-6">
					Gravitation between identities generates specific forms of tension:
				</p>
				<ul class="space-y-5 text-lg text-white/55">
					<li class="border-l border-white/15 pl-5">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Attractive tension:</strong> The pull toward alignment, collaboration, or orbit. This can be highly productive when visions resonate, but it can also create tension when one identity feels its own trajectory being bent too strongly by another.
					</li>
					<li class="border-l border-white/15 pl-5">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Orbital / relational tension:</strong> Once in each other’s gravitational field, identities must continuously negotiate distance, speed, and mutual influence. This is the tension of staying in productive orbit without collision or escape.
					</li>
					<li class="border-l border-white/15 pl-5">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Resistance tension:</strong> When one identity’s gravity is strong but misaligned, it can generate resistance and counter-tension in the other (the feeling of being pulled in a direction that conflicts with one’s own Sameness or Vision Gradient).
					</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 px-6 py-24">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Reading</div>
				<ul class="space-y-5">
					<li class="flex gap-3">
						<span class="text-violet-400">→</span>
						<span>Strong vision plus high mass means a deep well. Others feel drawn into orbit (collaborators, opportunities, attention) — and experience the tension of that pull.</span>
					</li>
					<li class="flex gap-3">
						<span class="text-violet-400">→</span>
						<span>Weak or incoherent mass means little pull, a flat field, noise competing equally — and little interactive tension to navigate.</span>
					</li>
					<li class="flex gap-3">
						<span class="text-violet-400">→</span>
						<span>Owned attraction differs from performance. Gravity persists when the spotlight moves — and so does the relational tension it creates.</span>
					</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 px-6 py-24">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<p>
					<strong class="text-white/80">Engineering work:</strong> Build attraction as a consequence of geometry, not as a marketing overlay. Deepen mass and clarify vision; let gravitation follow. At the same time, become sensitive to the interactive tension that strong gravitation inevitably creates in others — and in yourself when you are pulled by someone else’s field.
				</p>
				<div class="mt-8 rounded-2xl border border-white/10 bg-black/30 p-6">
					<div class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[3px] text-white/40 mb-3">Practical prompts</div>
					<ul class="space-y-3 text-white/60 leading-relaxed">
						<li>Which people or teams are repeatedly pulled into my orbit — and what tension does that create for them?</li>
						<li>Am I currently experiencing productive orbit or tension from being pulled in a direction that conflicts with my own trajectory?</li>
						<li>What alignment would increase high-quality attraction while keeping interactive tension manageable and generative?</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<ConceptPager id="gravitation" />
	</main>
</Layout>
